{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f5e8bdd-0f07-41f7-9516-b3f0673a7e4f","content":"Here's how to migrate from `VSTest@3` to Microsoft.Testing.Platform while keeping TRX reports and code coverage:\n\n## 1. Replace `VSTest@3` with `dotnet test`\n\nMicrosoft.Testing.Platform doesn't use `vstest.console.exe`, so replace the `VSTest@3` task with a `DotNetCoreCLI@2` task (or a plain `script` step):\n\n```yaml\n# BEFORE\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**/*Tests.dll'\n    runSettingsFile: test.runsettings\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n\n# AFTER\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration Release\n      --logger \"trx;LogFileName=TestResults.trx\"\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\n## 2. Publish TRX results\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish test results'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n```\n\n## 3. Publish code coverage\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish code coverage'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n> If using `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` (the Microsoft collector), the `.coverage` files are auto-published by Azure DevOps. For Cobertura XML, use `coverlet.collector` and pass `--collect:\"XPlat Code Coverage\"` instead.\n\n## Key differences from VSTest@3\n\n| Concern | VSTest@3 | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|---|\n| Test discovery | Scans built DLLs | Runs via `dotnet test` on `.csproj` |\n| TRX output | Built-in | `--logger trx` |\n| Code coverage | `codeCoverageEnabled: true` | `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` |\n| Result publish | Built-in | Separate `PublishTestResults@2` step |\n| `.runsettings` | `runSettingsFile` input | `--settings test.runsettings` |\n\nThe main takeaway: `VSTest@3` bundled test execution + result publishing in one task. With Microsoft.Testing.Platform you use `dotnet test` and separate publish steps.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06838fb2-8f84-4363-98ff-edd4594b5238","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is a general question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure DevOps CI pipelines. I can answer this from my knowledge.","outputTokens":722,"requestId":"5C3A:236247:A1041:C95BE:69F54AD5"},"id":"59f62026-ecf7-46dc-9193-8b75869aca86","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:52:50.862Z","parentId":"713da58a-b745-4a16-96c9-53a7a59bfca4"}
